# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-cider-vinegar
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] All acetic acid bacteria are rod-shaped and obligate aerobes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Acetic acid bacteria are airborne and are ubiquitous in nature.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] They are actively present in environments where ethanol is being formed as a product of the fermentation of sugars.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] They can be isolated from the nectar of flowers and from damaged fruit.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Other good sources are fresh apple cider and unpasteurized beer that has not been filter sterilized.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] In these liquids, they grow as a surface film due to their aerobic nature and active motility.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Fruit flies or vinegar eels are considered common vectors in the propagation of acetic acid bacteria.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] The growth of *Acetobacter* in wine can be suppressed through effective sanitation, by complete exclusion of air from wine in storage, and by the use of moderate amounts of sulfur dioxide in the wine as a preservative.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Vinegar is produced when acetic acid bacteria act on alcoholic beverages such as wine.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Specific oxidation reactions occur through oxidative fermentation, which creates vinegar as a byproduct.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] In the biotechnological industry, these bacteria's oxidation mechanism is exploited to produce a number of compounds such as l-ascorbic acid, dihydroxyacetone, gluconic acid, and cellulose.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Besides food industry, some acetic acid bacteria are used as biocatalysts for the industrial production of compounds.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] They are used as the important biocatalysts for the development of eco-friendly fermentation processes as an alternative to the chemical synthesis.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Some genera, such as *Acetobacter*, can oxidize ethanol to carbon dioxide and water using Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] Other genera, such as *Gluconobacter*, do not oxidize ethanol, as they do not have a full set of Krebs cycle enzymes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] As these bacteria produce acid, they are usually acid-tolerant, growing well below pH 5.0, although the pH optimum for growth is 5.4-6.3.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-bacteria] *Acetobacter xylinum* is able to synthesize cellulose, something normally done only by plants.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] As an eardrop it is used to treat infections of the ear canal.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] As a liquid it is used to flush the bladder in those who have a urinary catheter in an attempt to prevent infection or blockage.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] As a gel it may be used to adjust the pH of the vagina.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] It may also be applied to the cervix to help detect cervical cancer during screening.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] Side effects may include burning at the site of application.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] Use is not recommended in the ear in people who have a hole in the eardrum.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] It works against both bacterial and fungal causes of external ear infections.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] Acetic acid has been used medically since the time of Ancient Egypt.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid-medical-use] Acetic acid is more commonly used for external ear infections in the developing world than the developed.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetobacter] The acetic fermentation was demonstrated by Louis Pasteur, who discovered the first acetobacter - *Acetobacter aceti* - in 1864.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetobacter] In 1998, two strains of *Acetobacter* isolated from red wine and cider vinegar were named *Acetobacter oboediens* and *Acetobacter pomorum*.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetobacter] In 2000, *Acetobacter oboediens* and *Acetobacter intermedius* were transferred to *Gluconacetobacter* on the basis of 16S rRNA sequencing.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetobacter] In 2002, *Acetobacter cerevisiae* and *Acetobacter malorum* were identified by 16S rRNA sequence analysis of *Acetobacter* strains.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetobacter] In 2006, a strain of *Acetobacter* isolated from spoiled red wine was named *Acetobacter oeni*.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/acetobacter] The genus *Acetobacter* contains species which are important commensal bacteria in the gut microbiome of *Drosophila melanogaster.* The species *A. pomorum* specifically helps uphold the physiology and development of *D. melanogaster* through insulin/insulin-like growth factor signaling.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] '**Adams Pearmain**', also called '**Adam's Parmane**', is a cultivar of apple.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] It was introduced to the Horticultural Society of London in 1826 by Robert Adams, under the name '**Norfolk Pippin**'.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] The fruit is large, varying from two and a half inches to three inches high, and about the same in breadth at the widest part.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] It is pearmain-shaped, very even, and regularly formed.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] The skin is pale yellow tinged with green, and covered with delicate russet on the shaded side; but deep yellow tinged with red, and delicately streaked with livelier red on the side facing the sun.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] The flesh is reddish, crisp, juicy, rich, and sugary, with an agreeable and pleasantly perfumed flavor.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adams-pearmain] This Cultivar is a sibling of Reinette de Hollande, a hybrid between Reinette Franche’ and ‘Reinette des Carmes.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] An **adverse effect** is an undesired harmful effect resulting from a medication or other intervention, such as surgery.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] An adverse effect may be termed a "side effect", when judged to be secondary to a main or therapeutic effect.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The term complication is similar to adverse effect, but the latter is typically used in pharmacological contexts, or when the negative effect is expected or common.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] If the negative effect results from an unsuitable or incorrect dosage or procedure, this is called a medical error and not an adverse effect.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects are sometimes referred to as "iatrogenic" because they are generated by a physician/treatment.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Some adverse effects occur only when starting, increasing or discontinuing a treatment.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Using a drug or other medical intervention which is contraindicated may increase the risk of adverse effects.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects may cause complications of a disease or procedure and negatively affect its prognosis.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] They may also lead to non-compliance with a treatment regimen.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects of medical treatment resulted in 142,000 deaths in 2013 up from 94,000 deaths in 1990 globally.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The harmful outcome is usually indicated by some result such as morbidity, mortality, alteration in body weight, levels of enzymes, loss of function, or as a pathological change detected at the microscopic, macroscopic or physiological level.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] It may also be indicated by symptoms reported by a patient.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects may cause a reversible or irreversible change, including an increase or decrease in the susceptibility of the individual to other chemicals, foods, or procedures, such as drug interactions.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In clinical trials, a distinction is made between an adverse event and a serious adverse event.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Generally, any event which causes death, permanent damage, birth defects, or requires hospitalization is considered a serious adverse event.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The results of trials are often included in the labelling of the medication to provide information both for patients and the prescribing physicians.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The term "life-threatening" in the context of a serious adverse event refers to an event in which the patient was at risk of death at the time of the event; it does not refer to an event which hypothetically might have caused death if it were more severe.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In many countries, adverse effects are required by law to be reported, researched in clinical trials and included into the patient information accompanying medical devices and drugs for sale to the public.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Investigators in human clinical trials are obligated to report these events in clinical study reports.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Research suggests that these events are often inadequately reported in publicly available reports.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Because of the lack of these data and uncertainty about methods for synthesising them, individuals conducting systematic reviews and meta-analyses of therapeutic interventions often unknowingly overemphasise health benefit.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] To balance the overemphasis on benefit, scholars have called for more complete reporting of harm from clinical trials.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The Yellow Card Scheme is a United Kingdom initiative run by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) and the Commission on Human Medicines (CHM) to gather information on adverse effects to medicines.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] This includes all licensed medicines, from medicines issued on prescription to medicines bought over the counter from a supermarket.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The scheme also includes all herbal supplements and unlicensed medicines found in cosmetic treatments.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse drug reactions (ADRs) can be reported by a number of health care professionals including physicians, pharmacists and nurses, as well as patients.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In the United States several reporting systems have been built, such as the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS), the Manufacturer and User Facility Device Experience Database (MAUDE) and the Special Nutritionals Adverse Event Monitoring System.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] MedWatch is the main reporting center, operated by the Food and Drug Administration.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In Australia, adverse effect reporting is administered by the Adverse Drug Reactions Advisory Committee (ADRAC), a subcommittee of the Australian Drug Evaluation Committee (ADEC).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Reporting is voluntary, and ADRAC requests healthcare professionals to report all adverse reactions to its current drugs of interest, and serious adverse reactions to any drug.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] ADRAC publishes the Australian Adverse Drug Reactions Bulletin every two months.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The Government's Quality Use of Medicines program is tasked with acting on this reporting to reduce and minimize the number of preventable adverse effects each year.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse reaction reporting is an important component of New Zealand's pharmacovigilance activities.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The Centre for Adverse Reactions Monitoring (CARM) in Dunedin is New Zealand's national monitoring centre for adverse reactions.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] It collects and evaluates spontaneous reports of adverse reactions to medicines, vaccines, herbal products and dietary supplements from health professionals in New Zealand.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In Canada, adverse reaction reporting is an important component of the surveillance of marketed health products conducted by the Health Products and Food Branch (HPFB) of Health Canada.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Within HPFB, the Marketed Health Products Directorate leads the coordination and implementation of consistent monitoring practices with regards to assessment of signals and safety trends, and risk communications concerning regulated marketed health products.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] MHPD also works closely with international organizations to facilitate the sharing of information.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse reaction reporting is mandatory for the industry and voluntary for consumers and health professionals.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In principle, medical professionals are required to report all adverse effects related to a specific form of therapy.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In practice, it is at the discretion of the professional to determine whether a medical event is at all related to the therapy.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] As a result, routine adverse effects reporting often may not include long-term and subtle effects that may ultimately be attributed to a therapy.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Part of the difficulty is identifying the source of a complaint.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] A headache in a patient taking medication for influenza may be caused by the underlying disease or may be an adverse effect of the treatment.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In patients with end-stage cancer, death is a very likely outcome and whether the drug is the cause or a bystander is often difficult to discern.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Surgery may have a number of undesirable or harmful effects, such as infection, hemorrhage, inflammation, scarring, loss of function, or changes in local blood flow.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] They can be reversible or irreversible, and a compromise must be found by the physician and the patient between the beneficial or life-saving consequences of surgery versus its adverse effects.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] For example, a limb may be lost to amputation in case of untreatable gangrene, but the patient's life is saved.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Presently, one of the greatest advantages of minimally invasive surgery, such as laparoscopic surgery, is the reduction of adverse effects.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Other nonsurgical physical procedures, such as high-intensity radiation therapy, may cause burns and alterations in the skin.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In general, these therapies try to avoid damage to healthy tissues while maximizing the therapeutic effect.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Vaccination may have adverse effects due to the nature of its biological preparation, sometimes using attenuated pathogens and toxins.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Common adverse effects may be fever, malaise and local reactions in the vaccination site.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Very rarely, there is a serious adverse effect, such as eczema vaccinatum, a severe, sometimes fatal complication which may result in persons who have eczema or atopic dermatitis.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Diagnostic procedures may also have adverse effects, depending much on whether they are invasive, minimally invasive or noninvasive.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] For example, allergic reactions to radiocontrast materials often occur, and a colonoscopy may cause the perforation of the intestinal wall.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects can occur as a collateral or side effect of many interventions, but they are particularly important in pharmacology, due to its wider, and sometimes uncontrollable, use by way of self-medication.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Thus, responsible drug use becomes an important issue here.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects, like therapeutic effects of drugs, are a function of dosage or drug levels at the target organs, so they may be avoided or decreased by means of careful and precise pharmacokinetics, the change of drug levels in the organism in function of time after administration.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Adverse effects may also be caused by drug interaction.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] This often occurs when patients fail to inform their physician and pharmacist of all the medications they are taking, including herbal and dietary supplements.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The new medication may interact agonistically or antagonistically (potentiate or decrease the intended therapeutic effect), causing significant morbidity and mortality around the world.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Drug-drug and food-drug interactions may occur, and so-called "natural drugs" used in alternative medicine can have dangerous adverse effects.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The scientific field of activity associated with drug safety is increasingly government-regulated, and is of major concern for the public, as well as to drug manufacturers.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The distinction between adverse and nonadverse effects is a major undertaking when a new drug is developed and tested before marketing it.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] This is done in toxicity studies to determine the nonadverse effect level (NOAEL).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] These studies are used to define the dosage to be used in human testing (phase I), as well as to calculate the maximum admissible daily intake.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Most drugs have a large list of nonsevere or mild adverse effects which do not rule out continued usage.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] These effects, which have a widely variable incidence according to individual sensitivity, include nausea, dizziness, diarrhea, malaise, vomiting, headache, dermatitis, dry mouth, etc.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] These can be considered a form of pseudo-allergic reaction, as not all users experience these effects; many users experience none at all.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The Medication Appropriateness Tool for Comorbid Health Conditions in Dementia (MATCH-D) warns that people with dementia are more likely to experience adverse effects, and that they are less likely to be able to reliably report symptoms.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Sometimes, putative medical adverse effects are regarded as controversial and generate heated discussions in society and lawsuits against drug manufacturers.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] One example is the controversy as to whether autism was linked to the MMR vaccine (or to thiomersal, a mercury-based preservative used in some vaccines).
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] The alleged correlation has been widely discredited by a large number studies, and despite removal of thimerosal from most early childhood vaccines beginning with those manufactured in 2003, the rate of autism has not decreased as would be expected if it had been the causative agent.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] Another instance is the potential adverse effects of silicone breast implants, which led to class actions brought by tens of thousands of plaintiffs against manufacturers of gel-based implants, due to allegations of damage to the immune system which have not yet been conclusively proven.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/adverse-effect] In 1998, Dow Corning settled its remaining suits for $3.2 Billion and went into bankruptcy.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has large apples, weighing from 250 to 300 grams.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/aia-ilu] It is juicy, bittersweet, and has a weak aroma.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu is grown in nurseries, but is not widely propagated.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/aia-ilu] The Aia Ilu has low scab resistance and is resistant to powdery mildew.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] There is no high-quality clinical evidence that regular consumption of apple cider vinegar helps to maintain or lose body weight, or is effective to manage blood glucose and lipid levels.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Vinegar has historically been made with whatever sort of foods are available, and vinegars using fruits commonly available in the North Atlantic became popular in the early nineteenth century.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] One 1810 cookbook includes recipes for apple cider vinegar, gooseberry vinegar, and raisin vinegar.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Apples are washed, crushed, and pressed to extract the juice.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Autochthonous or inoculated yeasts, mainly Saccharomyces cerevisiae, initiate alcoholic fermentation, converting the sugars in the juice into ethanol and producing apple cider.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] The apple cider is then inoculated with either a pure culture of acetic acid bacteria or a proportion of 'mother vinegar', resulting in a secondary acetic fermentation which then converts the ethanol in the cider to acetic acid, yielding apple cider vinegar.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] The "mother" is a cellulose-rich biofilm of acetic bacteria that may remain in unfiltered vinegar.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Apple cider vinegar is 94% water and 5% acetic acid with 1% carbohydrates and no fat or protein.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] In a 100 gram reference amount, it provides 90 kilojoules (22 kcal) of energy, with negligible content of micronutrients.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Evidence for apple cider vinegar having any health effect is poor, such as for weight loss, glycemic control or skin infections.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Its use is not recommended for any therapy in medical guidelines of major public health organizations or regulatory agencies.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Moderate consumption of apple cider vinegar is safe, particularly if it is diluted, and the chance of side effects when it is consumed as directed and in the recommended amounts appears to be low.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Reported adverse effects include esophageal damage due to incomplete swallowing of apple cider vinegar tablets, tooth enamel damage due to swallowing excessive quantities of apple cider vinegar, and increased frequency of burping, flatulence, and bowel movements.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Consumption of vinegar can increase dentin hypersensitivity.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Irritation and redness are common when the eyes come into contact with vinegar, and corneal injury can occur.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Using vinegar as a topical medication, ear cleaning solution, or eye wash is hazardous.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Although small amounts of apple cider vinegar may be used as a food flavoring, it may be unsafe for use by pregnant and breastfeeding women and by children.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Different commercial brands of apple cider vinegar were found to have inconsistent acid levels, with some contaminated by molds and yeast.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] If used as a homemade cleaning agent, apple cider vinegar, like any kind of vinegar, should not be mixed with chlorine bleach, the combination of which may release chlorine gas and irritate airways, eyes, nose and throat.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] People with allergies to apples may experience allergic reactions to apple cider vinegar.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] Topical use of apple cider vinegar to treat skin diseases may cause burns.
[src:apple-cider-vinegar/apple-cider-vinegar] The use of apple cider vinegar may cause untoward interactions with prescription drugs, such as insulin or diuretics.
